<DESCRIPT>  FOOD; RECIPE  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  This sampler features recipes from celebrity chefs; lending their talents to
help feed AIDS patients  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Food  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  HELPING HAND  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Recipes of the Week  </MEMO>
<TEXT>  Some of the greatest culinary talents in California have joined forces to
create "The Open Hand Celebration Cookbook" (Simon &amp; Schuster, $22). The book
includes menus and recipes from 69 chefs. Columnist and chef Stanley
Eichelbaum, who compiled and edited the collection, sums up the theme as "fun
and festivity: food as a celebration of life, food as a pleasurable
accompaniment to a joyous occasion." Featured occasions include a feast for
Ramadan and a football-watching party in front of the TV. A portion of the
book's proceeds will benefit San Francisco's Project Open Hand, a food service
that delivers freshly prepared meals to people with AIDS.; PEAR AND SWEET
POTATO SOUP; 1 tablespoon olive oil; 1 onion, sliced; 3 ribs celery, sliced; 3
leeks, mostly whites, cleaned and sliced; 3 shallots, chopped; 1/4 cup peeled,
chopped ginger; 4 pears, peeled and cored; 4 sweet potatoes, peeled and cut
into small pieces; 4 cups chicken or vegetable stock; Salt and white pepper to
taste; 1/2 cup low-fat yogurt, plus extra for garnish; Pickled ginger for
garnish (optional);  Heat olive oil in a large pan, and saute onion, celery,
leeks, shallots and ginger until translucent. Add pears (reserve some pear for
garnish), sweet potatoes and stock. Stir, and bring to a boil. Reduce heat and
allow to simmer for 45 minutes. Season with salt and pepper. Puree the soup in
a blender or food processor. Set aside and chill.;   When soup is cold, whisk
in the yogurt. Serve cold, garnished with a dollop of yogurt, a slice of
pickled ginger (if using) and the reserved diced pear. Makes 6 servings.;   --
From Peter M. DeMarais,; executive sous-chef,; Sheraton Palace Hotel,; San
Francisco; FUSILLI WITH RICOTTA CHEESE; 4 cups ricotta cheese; 2 eggs; 3/4
teaspoon salt; 3/4 teaspoon black pepper; 1 cup cream; 12 ounces fusilli
pasta; 4 tablespoons finely chopped parsley; Grated Parmesan cheese;  In an
electric mixer fitted with the paddle attachment, mix the ricotta, eggs, salt
and pepper. Beat well for 4 to 5 minutes, until the mixture becomes fluffy. On
slow speed, gradually add the cream, and beat until incorporated. The mixture
should be thick but saucelike.;   Cook the pasta in boiling, salted water
until al dente. Drain the fusilli of all but a bit of cooking water (a little
will keep the pasta moist). Transfer to a bowl. Quickly toss with the ricotta
mixture and parsley. Serve with Parmesan cheese. Makes 4 servings.;   -- From
Donna Nicoletti, chef and part owner,; Undici restaurant,; San Francisco;
CHICKEN VESUVIO; 2 pounds small roasting potatoes, cleaned and cut in half;
Olive oil; 3 teaspoons chopped garlic; 2 teaspoons dried oregano; Salt and
pepper to taste; 2 frying chickens, 2 1/2 pounds each, cut into thighs,
drumsticks, half-breasts and wings;  On a baking sheet, toss the potatoes with
olive oil, 1 teaspoon of the garlic, 1 teaspoon oregano and a good amount of
salt and pepper. The olive oil should lightly coat the potatoes. Bake in a
preheated 400-degree oven for 30 minutes, turning occasionally.;   Heat some
oil in a saute pan. Season the chicken pieces with salt and pepper, and sear,
skin-side down. Toss in remaining garlic. Sprinkle remaining oregano on the
chicken, making sure not to drop it into the oil, as it will burn. Turn the
chicken, and sear the other side. Transfer to a baking pan, and roast in a
400-degree oven, 20 minutes for the breasts and 30 minutes for the other
parts. Serve with the potatoes. Makes 4 servings.;   -- From Donna Nicoletti;
WOLFGANG'S FRUITCAKE; 1 cup Marsala wine; 1 cup water; 1 cup raisins; 1 cup
dried apricots; 1 cup walnuts; 1/2 cup dried pears; 1/2 cup dried figs; 1/2
cup pecans; 1/2 cup (1 stick) unsalted butter; 1/2 cup sugar; 1 teaspoon
ground cinnamon; 1/4 teaspoon ground cloves; 2 cups all-purpose flour; 2
teaspoons baking soda; 1/2 teaspoon salt;  Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Butter
8 1/2-by-4-by-3 1/2 loaf pan. Dust with flour. In a medium saucepan, combine
Marsala, water, raisins, apricots, walnuts, pears, figs and pecans. Simmer
until fruits are tender, about 5 minutes. Cool.;   Drain, reserving liquid.
Coarsely chop fruits and nuts. Transfer to large bowl with reserved liquid. In
small saucepan, melt butter with sugar, cinnamon and cloves, stirring
occasionally, until sugar is completely dissolved. Cool.;   Meanwhile, in
bowl, sift together flour, baking soda and salt. Stir in melted-butter
mixture. Pour batter into fruits and nuts, combining thoroughly. Scrape into
prepared pan and level out.;   Bake 60 to 70 minutes, until cake is firm to
touch and nicely browned. Invert onto parchment-lined wire rack. Cool. Wrap
well. To serve, cut into thin slices. Serves 6 or more.;   -- From Wolfgang
Puck,; owner of Spago restaurant,; Los Angeles; PEARS POACHED IN GINGER; 12
Seckel pears, peeled; Juice of 1 lemon; 1 cup sugar; 1/4 pound ginger, peeled
and thinly sliced crosswise; 1 bottle sparkling wine;  After peeling pears,
place in bowl of cold water with lemon juice. Put sugar in a large enamel pot
over medium heat until sugar caramelizes. Add pears and ginger, mixing well to
coat pears with caramel. Add sparkling wine and cook over low heat for about
20 minutes. Remove pears with slotted spoon and place on platter. Cook down
poaching liquid to a syrup. Pour over pears with ginger slices and serve warm
or cold. Serves 12.; -- From Chef Mark Malicki,; Iron Horse Vineyards,;
Sebastopol; SPINACH SALAD AND TOASTED HAZELNUT VINAIGRETTE; Vinaigrette:; 1/4
cup hazelnuts, toasted, skinned and chopped; 3/4 cup fresh orange juice,
reduced by half and cooled; 1/4 cup rice vinegar; 1/4 cup chardonnay; 3/4 cup
olive oil; 1/8 cup hazelnut oil; 2 tablespoons finely chopped red onion; 2
tablespoons chopped Italian parsley; Salt and pepper to taste; Salad:; 1 pound
spinach leaves, stemmed ans washed; 2 Asian pears, cored and thinly sliced;
1/2 pound American blue cheese; 8 edible flowers (optional);  For vinaigrette,
mix all ingredients and allow to stand several hours before serving.;   For
salad, the spinach leaves should be tossed in a chilled bowl with 1/8 cup
vinaigrette per person. The pear slices should be added at the last minute.
Place the dressed salad on plates and crumble blue cheese over it. The flowers
can be chopped and placed over the salad, or left whole as a garnish.;   --
From Charles Saunders, former executive chef,; Sonoma Mission Inn &amp; Spa  </TEXT>
