<DESCRIPT>  MOVIE; REVIEW  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  TIME was Frankie and Johnny were content to be just down-and-dirty lovers.
Today, in the Al Pacino-Michelle Pfeiffer movie carrying their names, they're
New Yawk neurotic, deeply troubled and insecure. We know they'll eventually
collapse into each other's arms, more out of exhaustion than any belief they
are "made for each other." But this won't happen until much soul-searching and
hollow protestations, especially by Frankie.;   "Frankie &amp; Johnny," you see,
is one of those brash "modern" romances that reverses the formula by
demonstrating, in dispiriting detail, why two lonely hearts don't have a
chance at happiness. But then, after pummeling them -- and us -- for two
hours, it reverts to the safe "Happily ever after . . ." fade-out.  </LEADPARA>
